According to theſe Principles I have laid down, I cannot but recommend an open, free, and uninterrupted Air, a ſandy Soil, a ſituation upon the higheſt Ground, free from Hills, Woods, or any thing elſe that may intercept this Sweet and Balſamick Air: And I wonder that our Anceſtors did ſo little regard theſe things, when even ſome of the Poets took notice of it. As Lucan, deſcribing the Plague in Pompey's Army, tells us, how free Caeſar's (though near

him) was from it upon the higher Ground, while it raged in Pompey's Army below;


At liber terrae ſpatioſis collibus hoſtis

Aere non pigro, nec inertibus angitur undis;
                   which may ſerve for a good Caution to all Encamping Generals.
